PART 2: WHY IS I(T;H)/m ≈ 0.27?
  Decomposition: I(T;H) = H(H) (entropy of H distribution)
  H(H) ≈ log2(#H values) * efficiency
  So I/m ≈ log2(#H values) / m * efficiency
======================================================================
  n=3: m= 3, #H_values=  2, log2(#H)=1.000, log2(#H)/m=0.3333
  n=4: m= 6, #H_values=  3, log2(#H)=1.585, log2(#H)/m=0.2642
  n=5: m=10, #H_values=  7, log2(#H)=2.807, log2(#H)/m=0.2807
  n=6: m=15, #H_values= 19, log2(#H)=4.248, log2(#H)/m=0.2832
  n=7: m=21, #H_values= 77, log2(#H)=6.267, log2(#H)/m=0.2984

  Pattern: log2(#H values) / m is NOT constant:
  It ranges from 0.26 to 0.33, with mean ≈ 0.28
  The efficiency factor (≈0.95-0.98) brings it closer to 0.27

